            <div>
               <p><strong class="burnsred">Notes to the Text</strong></p>
                <div id="edn1">
                <a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" title="">1.</a> The source poem  belongs to the sequence <em>Black Light: poems in memory of George Seferis</em> (Burns 1983; reprinted in Berengarten 2008a, pp. 147-176). </p>
                <p><em>Black Light</em> has been  translated into four languages other than English: Serbo-Croat (Burns 1986, tr.  Bogdana G. Bobi&#263;); German (Burns 1996,&nbsp;  tr. Theo Breuer); Slovenian (Burns 2000, tr. Ana Jelnikar); and Greek  (Burns 2004, tr. Nasos Vayenas and Ilias Layios). &lsquo;Volta&rsquo; had also been  translated into Italian (Burns 2007, tr. Paola Musa); and into Spanish (Burns  2007: 4-5, tr. Miguel Teruel and Paul S. Derrick). Together with the essay by  Maria Filippakopoulou  referred to in note 2 below, the existence of these  translations first gave me the idea for the present anthology. The translations  of &lsquo;Volta&rsquo; by Theo Breuer, Ana Jelnikar, Ilias Layios, Paola  Musa, Miguel Teruel and Paul S. Derrick all appear here. </p>
                <p>The title <em>Black  Light</em> derives from a line in &lsquo;Thrush&rsquo;, a poem by Seferis (Seferis 1969:  330-331). The ideas in Seferis&rsquo;s mind that underlie this phrase are explored  further in an entry in his journal (see Seferis 1991: 31). &lsquo;Volta&rsquo; contains a  further reference to Seferis in its epigraph (Seferis 1969: 110-111), as well  as the Greek word <em>Eleftheria</em> (<em>&#904;&lambda;&epsilon;&upsilon;&theta;&epsilon;&rho;&#943;&alpha;</em>), meaning &lsquo;Freedom&rsquo;, and  a girl&rsquo;s name.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn2">
                <p><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" title="">2.</a>See the essay by  Maria Filippakopoulou, &lsquo; <a href="http://interlitq.org/issue9/filippakopoulou/job.php" class="link1">Foreign in our own  country</a>&rsquo; in this issue of the <em>International Literary Quarterly </em>. See also her commentary on &lsquo;Volta&rsquo; in the  same essay.  Another relevant essay is her  &lsquo;Common miracle&rsquo;, in Filippakopoulou 2005: 46-51. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn3">
                <p><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3" title="">3.</a> Geographically  and historically, I consider the Mediterranean as a kind of  &lsquo;continent&rsquo; in its own right, including its coastlines and islands: one whose  fuzzy margins are thinkable even if not precisely mappable in terms of  proximity to its mantle of water.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn4">
                <p><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4" title="">4.</a> See Weinreich  1945: 3-18; and also Weinreich 1946 (1999).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn5">
                <p><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5" title="">5.</a> I consider these  qualities indispensable for the fullest attainment in poetry. For preliminary  statements, see Berengarten 2002, footnote 4; and Berengarten 2009a.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn6">
                <p><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" title="">6.</a> The asterisk  before the expression denotes that it is not one that is actually used &ndash; in  this case, in English.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn7">
                <p><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7" title="">7.</a> The custom is  known as the &lsquo;Sabbath Stroll&rsquo;. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn8">
                <p><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8" title="">8.</a> <em>Vuelta</em> was the name of the literary magazine edited by Octavio Paz from 1975 until his  death in 1998. I am indebted to Anthony Rudolf for reminding me of this.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn9">
                <p><a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9" title="">9.</a> The coinage <em>elseness</em> here is intended as rather more than an alternative to the words <em>otherness</em> and <em>alterit</em>y,both of which are familiar in philosophical and  sociological writing, for example in English translations of the works of  Jacques Derrida and Emmanuel L&eacute;vinas, and in the books of Zygmunt Bauman. </p>
                <p>First, in deploying the word <em>elseness</em> as an antonym for <em>ownness</em>, I mean to imply that the former indicates the idea of &lsquo;being another&rsquo;, or  &lsquo;belonging or appertaining to another&rsquo;. </p>
                <p>Secondly, and perhaps more interestingly, by <em>elseness</em> I also  intend a precise antonym for the word <em>thisness</em>, with specific reference  to the development by Gerard Manley Hopkins of his concepts <em>inscape</em> and <em>instress</em>, out of Duns Scotus&rsquo;s Latin word <em>haecceitas</em>. The difference between <em>thisness</em> and <em>elseness</em> might also be clarified in the following correlation: that  if both words were to adhere to or imply the presence (or experience) of  glory, then the former would indicate <em>immanent</em> and the latter <em>transcendent</em> glory. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn10">
                <p><a href="#_ednref10" name="_edn10" title="">10.</a> A line from  George Herbert&rsquo;s poem &lsquo;Jordan (I)&rsquo;, published in <em>The Temple</em>, 1633. See  Herbert 1961: 48-9.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn11">
                <p><a href="#_ednref11" name="_edn11" title="">11.</a> Pushkin wrote: &ldquo;The translator is the post-horse of enlightenment.&rdquo; Quoted in Ishov (4: footnote 10). I am indebted to  Anthony Rudolf for drawing my attention to this reference.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn12">
                <p><a href="#_ednref12" name="_edn12" title="">12.</a> In connection  with the discussion in this section, See Walter Benjamin&rsquo;s classic essay, &lsquo;The  Task of the Translator&rsquo;, some of whose arguments differ considerably in  emphasis from those in this piece:</p>
                <blockquote>
                  <p>&nbsp;[I]t is not the highest praise of a  translation, particularly in the age of its origin, to say that it reads as if  it had originally been written in that language. Rather, the significance of  fidelity as ensured by literalness is that the work reflects the great longing  for linguistic complementation. A real translation is transparent; it does not  cover the original, does not block its light, but shows the pure language, as  though reinforced by its own medium, to shine upon the original all the more  fully. (Benjamin: 79).&nbsp; </p>
                </blockquote>
                <p>As  indicated in his phrases &ldquo;great longing&rdquo; and &ldquo;pure language&rdquo; here, as well as  in the quasi-mystical suggestion latent in the presence of &ldquo;light&rdquo; in  association with the idea of the &ldquo;original&rdquo;, I believe the main tendency in  Benjamin&rsquo;s essay &ndash; whether he would have admitted it or not &ndash; is in the  direction of a transcendental <em>Tikkun</em>. This is a Hebrew word close in  meaning to &lsquo;mending&rsquo;, &lsquo;repairing&rsquo;, &lsquo;restitution&rsquo; and hence to &lsquo;desire for  original purity, cleanness, wholeness, etc.&rsquo; &ndash; as explored throughout the  writings of Benjamin&rsquo;s friend, Gershom Scholem, on the Kabbalah (see especially  Scholem 1991). By contrast, in focusing on translation as border/line, and on  &lsquo;language x&rsquo; as a concomitant tension between language A and B and an epiphany  arising from their conjunction, my concerns in this essay are more to do with  immanence and residue.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn13">
                <p><a href="#_ednref13" name="_edn13" title="">13.</a> See especially  Borges&rsquo; text,&nbsp; &lsquo;Pierre Menard, Author of  the <em>Quixote</em>&rsquo;, published in <em>Ficciones</em>, 1944 (<em>Fictions</em>). For  an Internet version in English, see <a href="http://www.coldbacon.com/writing/borges-quixote.html" class="link1">http://www.coldbacon.com/writing/borges-quixote.html</a>.   </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn14">
                <p><a href="#_ednref14" name="_edn14" title="">14.</a> The words <em>verse</em> and <em>version</em> both derive from the Latin word meaning &lsquo;turn&rsquo; &ndash; the former  from Latin <em>versus</em>, &ldquo;a line or row, spec. a line of writing (so named  from turning to begin another line)&rdquo; (<em>Oxford English Dictionary</em> online). This etymology  further re-emphasises the idea explored in Section 5:  that in the making of a translation, the turning that is involved in writing  verse itself undergoes a &lsquo;re-turning&rsquo;. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn15">
                <p><a href="#_ednref15" name="_edn15" title="">15.</a> Auerbach 1953.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn16">
                <p><a href="#_ednref16" name="_edn16" title="">16.</a> Deleuze and  Guattari 2004: 117. On p. 581, the embedded quotation from Pier Paolo Pasolini  is referenced (see Pasolini 1976) but with no page number.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn17">
                <p><a href="#_ednref17" name="_edn17" title="">17.</a> <em>Mandelbrot </em>1977: 31. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn18">
                <p><a href="#_ednref18" name="_edn18" title="">18.</a> <em>Mandelbrot </em>1977: 25. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn19">
                <p><a href="#_ednref19" name="_edn19" title="">19.</a> I am indebted to  Melanie Rein for this observation.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn20">
                <p><a href="#_ednref20" name="_edn20" title="">20.</a> <em>Mandelbrot </em>1977: 27. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn21">
                <p><a href="#_ednref21" name="_edn21" title="">21.</a> See Steiner&rsquo;s key  essay &lsquo;Extra-territorial&rsquo; in his book of the same title (1972: 3-11). The  difficulty, however, with this word is that it embeds a tautology, for the  condition of extra-territoriality necessarily implies expansion or movement to  a new, wider area of territoriality, whether by for example, migrancy, exile or  colonialism. As already suggested, it is hard if not impossible to avoid  spatial metaphors in this kind of discussion. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn22">
                <p><a href="#_ednref22" name="_edn22" title="">22.</a> Donne 1624 (1959: 108-9).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn23">
                <p><a href="#_ednref23" name="_edn23" title="">23.</a> Paz 1961: 162. I  have changed the word &lsquo;mankind&rsquo; in Lysander Kemp&rsquo;s translation to &lsquo;humanity&rsquo;,  because Paz&rsquo;s idea does not require gender-marking and is diminished by it. </p>
                <p>This sentence of  Paz is one of the foundations of my poetics, which I have been glad to iterate  as a recurrent motif: for example, in Burns 1972, reprinted in Berengarten 2008a:  23; in the postscript to <em>The Manager</em>, Salt Publishing, Cambridge, Berengarten  2008b: 161; and in Berengarten 2009: 151 &amp; 159-160. The last of these  references may serve as an additional guideline to the &lsquo;Volta&rsquo; project:</p>
                <blockquote>
                  <p>In  the wake of Paz, I have argued since 1971 that single monolithic &lsquo;centres&rsquo;,  especially national and nationalistic ones, are anathema, that difference is a  cause for happiness, multiplicity a cue for celebration, and pluralism a  prospect for hope. </p>
                </blockquote>
              </div>
              <div id="edn24">
                <p><a href="#_ednref24" name="_edn24" title="">24.</a> Deleuze and Guattari  2004: 114.</p>
